<br>
Every day I see or hear members of the supposedly 'goodly' races and classes committing vile acts. They murder guards and citizenry, advocate violence and cruelty beyond what I would ever do, and slaughter their own gods' avatar forms. Examples include the vile &quot;Lust For Blood&quot; ((OOC: no offense)), who advocate bloody strife everywhere they go.<br>
<br>
And yet I am treated like the villain here. I am tired of this double standard. Which speaks louder?! Class and supposed beliefs (ones I do not even practice or believe in?!) or actions? Eh? So I am a knight of the shadows. Are not some of those who battle the avatar of Tunare herself her druids, rangers, and clerics?! If they can go against their source of power, why can't I?<br>
<br>
((OOC: sorry, had to rant. What do you think about this?)) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dididaryth>Didi D Aryth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Worshipping Tallonar since 3160</span><br>  Posts: 1251<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/29/03 9:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4677.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://users.bigpond.net.au/stbt/didi/a_didisig.gif height=120 width=120></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Double Standards</span><hr size=1> Well, a difficult topic for a young one to consider.  I too am a follower of the shadows, and I observe the corrupt deeds of those who claim to follow the &quot;light&quot; on a daily basis.  I am not quite certain what the exact question in your mind is, but it raises a few responses in my thoughts:<br>
<br>
1.  The appropriate behaviour towards one's god is largely dependent on one's god.  I, for example, worship the true father, Innoruuk.  When I enter His realm, I expect His minions to challenge my right to be there, and to test my strength and my hate through battle.  Were I to meet the Father face to face, I do not think he would expect warm greetings and hugs, as the revolting Tunare likely expects from her followers.  Likewise, I imagine that Rallos Zek would delight to engage his true worshippers in battle.  On the other hand, it does seem unlikely that a true follower of Tunare or Erollisi Marr would raise their hands in battle against these deities.  Thus, what you might call a double standard for one god's worshipper is not necessarily a double standard for the worshipper of another god.<br>
<br>
2. The members of Lust for Blood are not a good example so-called of &quot;goodly&quot; classes advocating murder and mayhem.  It's my understanding that Lust for Blood recruits only the most depraved, violent, and despicable individuals of any race, those willing to put the glorification of violence above any religious or racial alliance.  Point rather at those masquerading as pure and good in heart and deed, who do not openly admit they embrace violence, greed, and lust for battle, yet who do so.<br>
<br>
3. The so-called &quot;dark&quot; races are in many way equally to fault.  Do you see dark elves in the embrace of high elven lovers?  Shadow knights assisting druids?  Many, Shintou being a particularly infamous speaker on this topic, would call that equally two-faced and denounce these traitors just as one would think a paladin slaying dwarven guards should be denounced.<br>
<br>
4. One must acknowledge that in all races, religions, and professions there are some members who are a disgrace to their god and guildmasters.  Yet, the noble houses of Neriak, like House D'Aryth, should not be judged by the actions of those degenerate teir'dal who are outcast from Neriak and who choose to associate with paladins and similar filth.  Likewise I suppose it is possible that the reverse situation exists from the point of view of those of light-loving ilk.  One must follow one's own path and establish one's own reputation, regardless of what others may expect or assume.<br>
<br>
5. The true question in my mind is why the gods do not disown those who use their magics and powers to act against the wishes of those gods.  If Innoruuk were to withdraw his divine gifts from those who allied with Kelethin or harmed the guards of Neriak, my satisfaction would be great indeed.  And imagine the number of powerless paladins that the world would see.  It would be a sweet day indeed. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><br>
